	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Non- implementation of commitments and complex procedures hold back intra-regional trade in Ghana and Nigeria</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 July 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A policy note published by the World Bank has reviewed the barriers to trade between Ghana and Nigeria. These two economies account for 61% of the population and 68% of the GDP of the ECOWAS region, so these barriers can be taken as symptomatic of wider obstacles to intra-regional trade, particularly in view of the barriers that exist to the overland transit trade through Togo and Benin.</p><p>According to the World Bank analysis, regional integration in West Africa is lagging behind expectations, as political commitments have not yet been translated into policy and regulatory reforms. The analysis notes that ‘the existing scheme for regional free trade faces significant challenges’, while ‘there is still no agreement at the ECOWAS level on the precise structure of the common external tariff.’</p><p>In terms of intra-regional free trade, this is governed by the ‘ECOWAS Trade Liberalization Scheme (ETLS)’, which was nominally established in 1983 and launched in 1990. ‘Under the ETLS, preferential tariffs for intra-regional trade are set at 0 percent, and products should not face any quantitative restriction.’ In principle, the ETLS ‘covers all products of community origin, and aims to ensure free movement of goods and persons within ECOWAS’.</p><p>However, the share of intra-regional trade has remained low, in part because these long-standing commitments are extremely complex to implement. In effect, ‘registration is needed for every individual product a company intends to export under the scheme.’ In addition, ‘even when a product is registered and all information provided, crossing the border can be difficult: additional payments always seem to be necessary, and the importation of products can be outright prohibited.’</p><p>For example, in the application of import bans Nigerian customs officials make no distinction between ECOWAS and third-country originating products. This is in contradiction with the ETLS, ‘which specifically determines that regional exporters should not be subject to quantitative restrictions’. Thus, according to the policy note, ‘intra-regional trade is not duty or quota free, and borders present substantial barriers to regional integration.’</p><p>In the area of food products in particular, these difficulties are compounded by the certification requirements from the National Agency for Food and Drug Administration Control (NAFDAC) which are ‘complex and burdensome’ with ‘excessive’ registration fees that are often 10 to 15 times higher for imported than for local products. Companies also have to register every product type by package size. Further registration requirements linked to the Standards Organization of Nigeria (SON) add to this administrative and financial burden.</p><p>Equally Ghana sometimes blocks the duty-free importation of goods originating in ECOWAS, and applies a large number of additional taxes and fees that are not customs duties but that are charged on all imports. The government of Ghana ‘continues to apply (temporary) import bans and quotas for a few, mostly agricultural items.’</p><p>On the subject of intra-regional trade, the World Bank policy note recommends:</p>
<ul>

<li>simplification of cross-border trading procedures and registration requirements;</li>

<li>mutual recognition of standards and certificates of conformity;</li>

<li>major simplification of the ETLS scheme;</li>

<li>the launching of a major drive for transparency in border crossing procedures;</li>

<li>promotion of behavioural change among customs officials and the establishment of appeals and adjudication procedures.&nbsp;</li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>World Bank, ‘Removing barriers to trade between Ghana and Nigeria: Strengthening regional integration by implementing ECOWAS commitments’, by M. Hoppe and F. Aidoo, <i>Policy Note</i> No. 30, March 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/AFRICAEXT/EXTAFRREGTOPTRADE/0,,contentMDK:23155666~pagePK:34004173~piPK:34003707~theSitePK:502469,00.html" target="_self">http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/AFRICAEXT/EXTAFRREGTO...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Under ECOWAS rules, unprocessed products such as agricultural products should move freely from one member state to another, free from quantitative and quota restrictions and any administrative obstacles. However, there are many examples of non-implementation of free-trade policy commitments within ECOWAS. Ghanaian agricultural exports to Nigeria affected by bans and other import restrictions include, among others, cocoa products and cassava-based products, although such imports from Nigeria can easily enter the Ghanaian market.</p><p>Traders in the region are particularly interested in Nigeria’s huge market of about 140 million people, where analysts believe that the country's import prohibition may be responsible for some of the prohibitive business policies implemented by the Ghanaian government. The private-sector players in Nigeria are adding their voice to these debates by urging political leaders to honour the ETLS, realising that the frictions they encounter doing business within the ECOWAS sub-region are related to their own government’s policies.</p><p>Equally, seasonal and quantitative restrictions have been reported in the wider ECOWAS and UEMOA region. These affect – among many other products – seeds entering Mali and Niger, and cotton entering Ghana.</p><p>Effective regional trade integration needs to go beyond nominal tariff elimination commitments to address operational application and the implementation of measures to free up the movement of goods across the region. This constitutes a substantial trade facilitation agenda which still needs to be addressed across West Africa. However, getting to grips with trade issues in trade between Ghana and Nigeria could provide a real lead in regional trade integration processes.</p>
		</div>
		
